{"html": "<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:4.571em;font-weight:bold;font-family:\"Segoe UI Historic\",\"Noto Sans Phoenician\",\"Noto Serif\",\"Arial Unicode MS\",serif\">𐤉𐤄𐤅𐤄</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.905em;font-weight:bold\">THE ANCIENT COVENANT RECORD</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.238em;font-style:italic\">Volume Four — Part Two</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#666666;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Torah — Fourth Book</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:3.048em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.333em;font-style:italic\">In the Wilderness</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:1.048em;font-weight:bold\">Chapters 20 through 36</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#666666;font-size:0.905em;font-style:italic\">The Final Wilderness Years — The Border Victories — The Tribal Assignments</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">PRIMARY MANUSCRIPT AUTHORITIES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em\">4QNuma (4Q23) · 4QNumb (4Q27) · 4QNumc (4Q28) · 4QNumd (4Q29)</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em\">4QNume (4Q30) · 4QNumf (4Q31) · 4QNumg (4Q32) · 4QNumh (4Q33)</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em\">4QNumi (4Q34) · 4QNumj (4Q35) · 4QNumk (4Q36) · 4QNuml (4Q37)</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em\">Ethiopian Orit Ge'ez — Beta Israel Ancient Canon</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE NOTES AT END OF EVERY CHAPTER</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#666666;font-size:0.762em;font-style:italic\">DSS  ·  ORIT GE'EZ  ·  MASORETIC VARIANT</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#777777;font-size:0.762em;font-style:italic;font-family:\"Segoe UI Historic\",\"Noto Sans Phoenician\",\"Noto Serif\",\"Arial Unicode MS\",serif\">YHWH / 𐤉𐤄𐤅𐤄 and The Creator only — no substitutions</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#777777;font-size:0.762em;font-style:italic\">All personal names in original Hebrew form throughout</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center;border-top:1.5px solid #888888;border-bottom:1.5px solid #888888;padding:0.35em 0;margin:0.6em 0\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">THE FINAL WILDERNESS YEARS — CHAPTERS 20 THROUGH 25</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 20  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Death of Miryam — The Waters of Merivah — The Death of Aharon</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And the people of Yisra'EL, the whole congregation, came into the wilderness of Tzin in the first month, and the people stayed in Kadesh. And Miryam died there and was buried there.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Now there was no water for the congregation. And they assembled themselves together against Moshe and against Aharon.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH spoke to Moshe, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:8  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Take the staff, and assemble the congregation, you and Aharon your brother, and tell the rock before their eyes to yield its water. So you shall bring water out of the rock for them and give drink to the congregation and their cattle.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:10  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then Moshe and Aharon gathered the assembly together before the rock, and he said to them: Hear now, you rebels — shall we bring water for you out of this rock?</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:11  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Moshe lifted up his hand and struck the rock with his staff twice, and water came out abundantly, and the congregation drank, and their livestock.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:12  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH said to Moshe and Aharon: Because you did not believe in me, to uphold me as holy in the eyes of the people of Yisra'EL, therefore you shall not bring this assembly into the land that I have given them.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:23  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH said to Moshe and Aharon at Mount Hor, on the border of the land of Edom:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:24  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Aharon shall be gathered to his people, for he shall not enter the land that I have given to the people of Yisra'EL, because you rebelled against my command at the waters of Merivah.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:25  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Take Aharon and El'azar his son and bring them up to Mount Hor.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:26  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And strip Aharon of his garments and put them on El'azar his son. And Aharon shall be gathered to his people and shall die there.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:28  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Moshe stripped Aharon of his garments and put them on El'azar his son. And Aharon died there on the top of the mountain. Then Moshe and El'azar came down from the mountain.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">20:29  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And when all the congregation saw that Aharon had perished, all the house of Yisra'EL wept for Aharon thirty days.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 20. The deaths of Miryam and Aharon and the waters of Merivah are attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 20 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 20:12 — because you did not believe in me, to uphold me as holy in the eyes of the people, therefore you shall not bring this assembly into the land. Moshe struck the rock instead of speaking to it. The consequence is his exclusion from the land. The ancient record does not elaborate Moshe's precise failure in a way that makes the punishment straightforwardly proportional to the act. Centuries of commentary have struggled with this verse. The ancient text states the consequence without providing a detailed theological explanation. YHWH's holiness before the people requires exact obedience from the leader. Moshe's failure — whatever its precise nature — is costly. The greatest prophet in Yisra'EL's history will see the land from a mountain and not enter it.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 21  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Bronze Serpent — The Song of the Well — Victories over Sihon and Og</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:4  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">From Mount Hor they set out by the way to the Red Sea, to go around the land of Edom. And the people became impatient on the way.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:5  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And the people spoke against The Creator and against Moshe: Why have you brought us up out of Egypt to die in the wilderness? For there is no food and no water, and we loathe this worthless food.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then YHWH sent fiery serpents among the people, and they bit the people, so that many people of Yisra'EL died.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And the people came to Moshe and said: We have sinned, for we have spoken against YHWH and against you. Pray to YHWH, that he take away the serpents from us. So Moshe prayed for the people.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:8  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH said to Moshe: Make a fiery serpent and set it on a pole, and everyone who is bitten, when he sees it, shall live.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:9  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">So Moshe made a bronze serpent and set it on a pole. And if a serpent bit anyone, he would look at the bronze serpent and live.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:17  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then Yisra'EL sang this song: Spring up, O well — sing to it.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:18  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The well that the princes made, that the nobles of the people dug, with the scepter and with their staffs. And from the wilderness they went on to Mattanah.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:21  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then Yisra'EL sent messengers to Sihon king of the Amorites, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:22  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Let me pass through your land. We will not turn aside into field or vineyard. We will not drink the water of a well. We will go by the King's Highway until we have passed through your territory.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:23  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But Sihon would not allow Yisra'EL to pass through his territory. He gathered all his people together and went out against Yisra'EL to the wilderness and came to Yahatz and fought against Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:24  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Yisra'EL defeated him with the edge of the sword and took possession of his land from the Arnon to the Yabbok, as far as to the Ammonites.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:33  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then they turned and went up by the way to Bashan. And Og the king of Bashan came out against them, he and all his people, to battle at Edre'i.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:34  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But YHWH said to Moshe: Do not fear him, for I have given him into your hand, and all his people, and his land. And you shall do to him as you did to Sihon king of the Amorites, who lived at Heshbon.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">21:35  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">So they defeated him and his sons and all his people, until he had no survivor left. And they possessed his land.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 21. The bronze serpent account and the victories over Sihon and Og are attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 21 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 21:8-9 — make a fiery serpent and set it on a pole, and everyone who is bitten, when he sees it, shall live. The instrument of healing is fashioned in the image of the thing that caused the wound. The bronze serpent is YHWH's prescribed remedy — not an amulet or an idol, but a covenant act of looking toward what YHWH designates. Melakhim Bet 18:4 records that Hizkiyahu broke the bronze serpent — called Nakhash — because the people had begun burning incense to it. The instrument YHWH gave for healing in the wilderness had become an object of worship centuries later. Hizkiyahu's destruction of it is presented as a righteous covenant act.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 22  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">Balak Summons Bila'am — YHWH Speaks to Bila'am — The Donkey</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then the people of Yisra'EL set out and camped in the plains of Mo'av beyond the Yarden at Yeriho.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Balak the son of Tzippor saw all that Yisra'EL had done to the Amorites.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Mo'av was in great dread of the people, because they were many. Mo'av was overcome with fear of the people of Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:5  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">He sent messengers to Bila'am the son of Be'or at Petor, which is near the River in the land of the people of Amaw, to call him, saying: Behold, a people has come out of Egypt. They cover the face of the earth, and they are dwelling opposite me.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Come now, curse this people for me, since they are too mighty for me. Perhaps I shall be able to defeat them and drive them from the land, for I know that he whom you bless is blessed, and he whom you curse is cursed.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:12  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And The Creator said to Bila'am: You shall not go with them. You shall not curse the people, for they are blessed.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:20  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And The Creator came to Bila'am at night and said to him: If the men have come to call you, rise, go with them. But only do what I tell you.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:22  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But The Creator's anger was kindled because he went, and the angel of YHWH took his stand in the way as his adversary. Now he was riding on the donkey, and his two servants were with him.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:28  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then YHWH opened the mouth of the donkey, and she said to Bila'am: What have I done to you, that you have struck me these three times?</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:31  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then YHWH opened the eyes of Bila'am, and he saw the angel of YHWH standing in the way, with his drawn sword in his hand. And he bowed down and fell on his face.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">22:35  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And the angel of YHWH said to Bila'am: Go with the men, but speak only the word that I tell you. So Bila'am went on with the princes of Balak.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 22. Significantly, a text about Bila'am the son of Be'or was discovered at Tell Deir 'Alla in the region of Transjordan — inscribed on plaster and dated to approximately 800 BCE — the only ancient extra-biblical text that names and describes Bila'am as a seer and prophet. The Tell Deir 'Alla inscription confirms Bila'am was a known historical figure in the ancient world, not only a Torah narrative character.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 22 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 22:28 — YHWH opened the mouth of the donkey, and she said to Bila'am. The donkey speaks. The ancient record presents this without explanation or qualification. YHWH opens the donkey's mouth and she questions her master in plain Hebrew speech. The donkey had seen the angel of YHWH three times when Bila'am — the renowned seer — saw nothing. The animal with no prophetic pretension perceives YHWH's messenger. The prophet who is hired to curse YHWH's people is rebuked by his own animal. The irony is deliberate and structural in the ancient text.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 23  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The First and Second Oracles of Bila'am</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Bila'am took up his discourse and said: From Aram Balak has brought me, the king of Mo'av from the eastern mountains — Come, curse Yaakov for me, and come, denounce Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:8  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">How can I curse whom The Creator has not cursed? How can I denounce whom YHWH has not denounced?</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:9  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">For from the top of the crags I see him, from the hills I behold him. Behold, a people dwelling alone, and not counting itself among the nations.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:10  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Who can count the dust of Yaakov or number the fourth part of Yisra'EL? Let me die the death of the upright, and let my end be like his.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:19  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The Creator is not a man, that he should lie, or a son of man, that he should change his mind. Has he said, and will he not do it? Or has he spoken, and will he not fulfill it?</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:20  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Behold, I received a command to bless — he has blessed, and I cannot revoke it.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:21  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">He has not beheld misfortune in Yaakov, nor has he seen trouble in Yisra'EL. YHWH their Creator is with them, and the shout of a king is among them.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">23:23  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">For there is no enchantment against Yaakov, no divination against Yisra'EL. Now it shall be said of Yaakov and Yisra'EL: What has The Creator done?</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 23. Bila'am's oracles are attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 23 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 23:19 — The Creator is not a man, that he should lie, or a son of man, that he should change his mind. Has he said, and will he not do it? This declaration from the mouth of a non-Israelite seer hired to curse Yisra'EL is one of the strongest statements of YHWH's covenant faithfulness in the entire Torah. Bila'am cannot curse what YHWH has blessed. The covenant declared to Avraham — those who bless you I will bless and those who curse you I will curse — operates against the most elaborate cursing operation Balak can mount. The hired prophet becomes an unwilling herald of the covenant's invincibility.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 24  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Third and Fourth Oracles — The Star out of Yaakov</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Bila'am lifted up his eyes and saw Yisra'EL camping tribe by tribe. And the Spirit of The Creator came upon him.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And he took up his discourse and said: The oracle of Bila'am the son of Be'or, the oracle of the man whose eye is opened,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:4  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The oracle of one who hears the words of The Creator, who sees the vision of the Almighty, falling down with his eyes uncovered:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:5  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">How lovely are your tents, O Yaakov, your encampments, O Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Water shall flow from his buckets, and his seed shall be in many waters. His king shall be higher than Agag, and his kingdom shall be exalted.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:9  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">He crouched, he lay down like a lion and like a lioness — who will rouse him up? Blessed are those who bless you, and cursed are those who curse you.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:15  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And he took up his discourse and said: The oracle of Bila'am the son of Be'or, the oracle of the man whose eye is opened,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:16  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The oracle of one who hears the words of The Creator, and knows the knowledge of the Most High, who sees the vision of the Almighty, falling down with his eyes uncovered:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:17  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">I see him, but not now — I behold him, but not near. A star shall come out of Yaakov, and a scepter shall rise out of Yisra'EL. It shall crush the forehead of Mo'av and break down all the sons of Sheth.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:18  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Edom shall be dispossessed — Se'ir also, his enemies, shall be dispossessed. Yisra'EL is doing valiantly.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">24:25  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then Bila'am rose and went back to his place. And Balak also went his way.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 24. The Star out of Yaakov oracle — verse 24:17 — is one of the most significant passages in the Qumran corpus. It is cited in the War Scroll (1QM) and in the Damascus Document (CD 7:18-20) and in 4QTestimonia (4Q175) as a key messianic or eschatological prophecy. The DSS community applied this oracle to their own historical moment.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 24 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 24:17 — a star shall come out of Yaakov, and a scepter shall rise out of Yisra'EL. The star and scepter oracle is cited three times in the DSS texts found at Qumran — in the War Scroll, the Damascus Document, and the Testimonia scroll. The DSS community read it as pointing to a coming military or royal figure who would arise from the covenant people. The oracle comes from a non-Israelite seer whose eyes are opened by YHWH's Spirit — twice described as falling down with eyes uncovered. Bila'am sees what he does not want to see and declares what Balak hired him to negate. The covenant people's future is pronounced over them by their enemy's own prophet.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 25  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Baal of Pe'or — Pinkhas — The Covenant of Peace</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">While Yisra'EL lived in Shittim, the people began to whore with the daughters of Mo'av.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These invited the people to the sacrifices of their deities, and the people ate and bowed down to their deities.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">So Yisra'EL yoked himself to Baal of Pe'or. And the anger of YHWH was kindled against Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And behold, one of the people of Yisra'EL came and brought a Midyanite woman to his family, in the sight of Moshe and in the sight of the whole congregation of the people of Yisra'EL, while they were weeping in the entrance of the tent of meeting.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">When Pinkhas the son of El'azar, son of Aharon the priest, saw it, he rose and left the congregation and took a spear in his hand</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:8  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And went after the man of Yisra'EL into the chamber and pierced both of them, the man of Yisra'EL and the woman through her belly. Thus the plague on the people of Yisra'EL was stopped.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:9  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Nevertheless, those who died by the plague were 24,000.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:11  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Pinkhas the son of El'azar, son of Aharon the priest, has turned back my wrath from the people of Yisra'EL, in that he was jealous with my jealousy among them, so that I did not consume the people of Yisra'EL in my jealousy.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:12  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Therefore say: Behold, I give to him my covenant of peace,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">25:13  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And it shall be to him and to his descendants after him the covenant of a perpetual priesthood, because he was jealous for his Creator and made atonement for the people of Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 25. The covenant of peace given to Pinkhas is attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 25 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 25:12-13 — the covenant of peace — brit shalom — and the covenant of perpetual priesthood given to Pinkhas. This is one of the few places in the Torah where YHWH initiates a new covenant with an individual outside the patriarchal line. The covenant with Pinkhas is explicitly named a brit shalom and a perpetual priesthood covenant. It is not given because Pinkhas is powerful or of high standing — El'azar's son is not yet in the high priestly succession at this point. It is given because he was jealous with YHWH's jealousy and acted to stop the covenant desecration. Zealousness for YHWH's honor, at personal risk, is the ground of the covenant grant.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center;border-top:1.5px solid #888888;border-bottom:1.5px solid #888888;padding:0.35em 0;margin:0.6em 0\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">THE SECOND CENSUS AND FINAL PREPARATIONS — CHAPTERS 26 THROUGH 36</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 26  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Second Census — The New Generation Numbered</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">After the plague, YHWH said to Moshe and to El'azar the son of Aharon the priest,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Take a census of all the congregation of the people of Yisra'EL, from twenty years old and upward, by their fathers' houses, all in Yisra'EL who are able to go to war.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:51  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">This was the list of the people of Yisra'EL, 601,730.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:52  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">YHWH spoke to Moshe, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:53  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Among these the land shall be divided for inheritance according to the number of names.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:55  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But the land shall be divided by lot. According to the names of the tribes of their fathers they shall inherit.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:63  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These were those listed by Moshe and El'azar the priest, who listed the people of Yisra'EL in the plains of Mo'av by the Yarden at Yeriho.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:64  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But among these there was not one of those listed by Moshe and Aharon the priest, who had listed the people of Yisra'EL in the wilderness of Sinai.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">26:65  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">For YHWH had said of them: They shall die in the wilderness. Not one of them was left, except Kalev the son of Yefunneh and Yehoshua the son of Nun.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 26.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 26 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verses 26:64-65 — not one of those listed in the first census remained except Kalev and Yehoshua. The second census is not merely an administrative re-count. It is the confirmation that the sentence of Chapter 14 was carried out to the letter. Every person listed in the first census who was twenty years and older at the time of the spies' rebellion is now dead. The second census numbers the new generation — the children of those who died in the wilderness — who will enter the land. The covenant judgment was complete. The covenant promise continues.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 27  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Daughters of Tzelofkhad — The Succession of Yehoshua</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then drew near the daughters of Tzelofkhad the son of Hefer, son of Gil'ad, son of Makhir, son of Menasheh, from the clans of Menasheh the son of Yosef. The names of his daughters were: Makhlah, No'ah, Hoglah, Milkah, and Tirzah.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And they stood before Moshe and before El'azar the priest and before the chiefs and all the congregation, at the entrance of the tent of meeting, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Our father died in the wilderness. He was not among the company of those who gathered themselves against YHWH in the company of Korakh, but died for his own sin. And he had no sons.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:4  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Why should the name of our father be taken away from his clan because he had no son? Give to us a possession among our father's brothers.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:5  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Moshe brought their case before YHWH.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH said to Moshe:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The daughters of Tzelofkhad are right. You shall give them possession of an inheritance among their father's brothers and transfer the inheritance of their father to them.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:8  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And you shall speak to the people of Yisra'EL, saying: If a man dies and has no son, then you shall transfer his inheritance to his daughter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:12  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">YHWH said to Moshe: Go up into this mountain of Avarim and see the land that I have given to the people of Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:13  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">When you have seen it, you also shall be gathered to your people, as your brother Aharon was gathered,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:16  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Let YHWH, The Creator of the spirits of all flesh, appoint a man over the congregation</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:17  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Who shall go out before them and come in before them, who shall lead them out and bring them in, that the congregation of YHWH may not be as sheep that have no shepherd.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:18  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">So YHWH said to Moshe: Take Yehoshua the son of Nun, a man in whom is the Spirit, and lay your hand on him.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:20  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">You shall invest him with some of your authority, that all the congregation of the people of Yisra'EL may obey.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:22  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Moshe did as YHWH commanded him. He took Yehoshua and made him stand before El'azar the priest and the whole congregation,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">27:23  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And he laid his hands on him and commissioned him as YHWH directed through Moshe.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 27. The case of the daughters of Tzelofkhad and the commissioning of Yehoshua are attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 27 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verses 27:1-7 — the daughters of Tzelofkhad present their case at the entrance of the tent of meeting before Moshe, El'azar, and the entire congregation, and YHWH rules in their favor. The Torah's inheritance legislation is amended in real time by the case brought by five women. Moshe does not rule on his own authority — he brings the case to YHWH. YHWH rules: the daughters are right. The covenant law has a mechanism for expanding and clarifying itself through specific cases brought before YHWH. The daughters of Tzelofkhad are named five times in the Torah — Bamidbar 27, 36, and Yehoshua 17. The ancient record remembers them by name.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 28  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Daily and Appointed Offerings</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">YHWH spoke to Moshe, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Command the people of Yisra'EL and say to them: My offering, my food for my food offerings, my pleasing aroma, you shall be careful to offer to me at its appointed time.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And you shall say to them: This is the food offering that you shall offer to YHWH — two male lambs a year old without blemish, as a regular burnt offering each day.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:9  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the Sabbath day, two male lambs a year old without blemish, and two tenths of an ephah of fine flour for a grain offering, mixed with oil, and its drink offering.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:11  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">At the beginnings of your months, you shall offer a burnt offering to YHWH: two bulls from the herd, one ram, seven male lambs a year old without blemish.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:16  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the fourteenth day of the first month is the Pesach of YHWH.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:17  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And on the fifteenth day of this month is a feast. Seven days shall unleavened bread be eaten.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">28:26  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the day of the firstfruits, when you offer a grain offering of new grain to YHWH at your Feast of Weeks, you shall have a holy convocation. You shall not do any ordinary work.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma and 4QNumb preserve portions of Chapter 28.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 28 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Chapter 28 provides the complete calendar of communal offerings linked to each appointed time — daily, Sabbath, new moon, Pesach, Shavuot. This is the liturgical complement to the feast calendar of Vayikra 23. Vayikra 23 defines when the appointed times occur and who observes them. Bamidbar 28-29 defines what offerings YHWH requires at each appointed time from the community. Together these two chapters constitute the full covenant calendar of Yisra'EL as given in the Torah.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 29  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Offerings of the Seventh Month — Yom Teru'ah, Yom Kippur, Sukkot</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">29:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the first day of the seventh month you shall have a holy convocation. You shall not do any ordinary work. It is a day for you to blow the trumpets.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">29:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the tenth day of this seventh month you shall have a holy convocation and afflict yourselves. You shall do no work.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">29:12  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the fifteenth day of the seventh month you shall have a holy convocation. You shall not do any ordinary work, and you shall keep a feast to YHWH seven days.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">29:35  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">On the eighth day you shall have a solemn assembly. You shall not do any ordinary work.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">29:39  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These you shall offer to YHWH at your appointed feasts, in addition to your vow offerings and your freewill offerings, for your burnt offerings, and for your grain offerings, and for your drink offerings, and for your peace offerings.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 29.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 29 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The seventh month is the most dense in the covenant calendar: Yom Teru'ah on the first day, Yom Kippur on the tenth, Sukkot from the fifteenth through the twenty-first, and the eighth day assembly. Sukkot has the most elaborate offering schedule of all the appointed times — seventy bulls are offered over seven days, decreasing by one each day. The seventy bulls are understood in ancient tradition as corresponding to the seventy nations of the world, making Sukkot not only an Yisra'ELi celebration but a priestly act on behalf of all nations.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 30  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Law of Vows — Men and Women</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">30:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Moshe spoke to the heads of the tribes of the people of Yisra'EL, saying: This is what YHWH has commanded.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">30:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">If a man vows a vow to YHWH, or swears an oath to bind himself by a pledge, he shall not break his word. He shall do according to all that proceeds out of his mouth.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">30:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">If a woman vows a vow to YHWH and binds herself by a pledge, while within her father's house in her youth,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">30:4  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And her father hears of her vow and of her pledge by which she has bound herself and says nothing to her, then all her vows shall stand, and every pledge by which she has bound herself shall stand.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">30:10  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But any vow of a widow or of a divorced woman, anything by which she has bound herself, shall stand against her.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 30.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 30 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 30:2 — he shall not break his word. He shall do according to all that proceeds out of his mouth. The covenant law of vows operates on the same principle as YHWH's own covenant faithfulness — the word spoken is binding. YHWH does not break his word. The covenant people are to reflect YHWH's character in their own speech. The vow law of Bamidbar 30 and the prohibition of false oaths in Vayikra 19 together constitute the Torah's ethics of speech as covenant obligation.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 31  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The War Against Midyan — Bila'am Killed</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">31:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">YHWH spoke to Moshe, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">31:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Avenge the people of Yisra'EL on the Midyanites. Afterward you shall be gathered to your people.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">31:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">So Moshe spoke to the people, saying: Arm men from among you for the war, that they may go against Midyan to execute YHWH's vengeance on Midyan.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">31:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">They warred against Midyan, as YHWH commanded Moshe, and killed every male.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">31:8  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">They killed the kings of Midyan with the rest of their slain: Evi, Rekem, Tzur, Hur, and Reva — the five kings of Midyan. And they also killed Bila'am the son of Be'or with the sword.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">31:16  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Behold, these, on Bila'am's advice, caused the people of Yisra'EL to act treacherously against YHWH in the incident of Pe'or, and so the plague came among the congregation of YHWH.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 31.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 31 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 31:8 — they killed Bila'am the son of Be'or with the sword. Bila'am, who could not curse Yisra'EL with his mouth, advised Mo'av and Midyan on how to cause Yisra'EL to curse themselves through the incident of Pe'or in Chapter 25. The four oracles of blessing he pronounced over Yisra'EL stand in the Torah. His death at the hands of the Yisra'ELi army closes his account in Bamidbar. The Tell Deir 'Alla inscription names Bila'am as a known seer in the ancient world of Transjordan. He exists in the ancient record as a real historical figure outside the Torah text.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 32  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Tribes of Re'uven and Gad — The Transjordan Settlement</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Now the people of Re'uven and the people of Gad had a very great number of livestock, and they saw the land of Ya'zer and the land of Gil'ad, and behold, the place was a place for livestock.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And the people of Gad and the people of Re'uven came and said to Moshe and to El'azar the priest and to the chiefs of the congregation:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:4  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The land that YHWH struck down before the congregation of Yisra'EL is a land for livestock, and your servants have livestock.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:5  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And they said: If we have found favor in your sight, let this land be given to your servants for a possession. Do not take us across the Yarden.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But Moshe said to the people of Gad and to the people of Re'uven: Shall your brothers go to the war while you sit here?</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:16  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then they came near to him and said: We will build sheepfolds here for our livestock, and cities for our little ones.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:17  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But we will take up arms, ready to go before the people of Yisra'EL, until we have brought them to their place. And our little ones shall live in the fortified cities because of the inhabitants of the land.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:20  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">So Moshe said to them: If you will do this, if you will take up arms to go before YHWH for the war,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:22  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And the land is subdued before YHWH — then after that you shall return and be free of obligation to YHWH and to Yisra'EL, and this land shall be your possession before YHWH.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">32:33  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Moshe gave to them — to the people of Gad and to the people of Re'uven and to the half-tribe of Menasheh the son of Yosef — the kingdom of Sihon king of the Amorites and the kingdom of Og king of Bashan, the land and its cities with their territories.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 32.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 32 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Transjordan settlement of Re'uven, Gad, and half of Menasheh creates the first territorial division of the covenant inheritance — east of the Yarden before the main inheritance west of the river is distributed. The covenant condition is explicit: the armed men of the eastern tribes must cross the Yarden and fight alongside the rest of Yisra'EL until the entire land is subdued. Only then may they return to their eastern inheritance. The territorial inheritance is conditional on shared covenant military obligation. No tribe takes its inheritance and abandons the others.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 33  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Stages of the Wilderness Journey — The Complete Itinerary</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These are the stages of the people of Yisra'EL, when they went out of the land of Egypt by their companies under the leadership of Moshe and Aharon.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Moshe wrote down their starting places, stage by stage, by command of YHWH, and these are their stages according to their starting places.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">They set out from Ra'amses in the first month, on the fifteenth day of the first month. On the day after the Pesach, the people of Yisra'EL went out triumphantly in the sight of all the Egyptians.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:38  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Aharon the priest went up Mount Hor at the command of YHWH and died there, in the fortieth year after the people of Yisra'EL had come out of the land of Egypt, on the first day of the fifth month.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:50  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH spoke to Moshe in the plains of Mo'av by the Yarden at Yeriho, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:51  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Speak to the people of Yisra'EL and say to them: When you pass over the Yarden into the land of Kena'an,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:52  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then you shall drive out all the inhabitants of the land from before you and destroy all their figured stones and destroy all their metal images and demolish all their high places.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">33:53  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And you shall take possession of the land and settle in it, for I have given the land to you to possess it.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 33. Verse 33:2 explicitly states that Moshe wrote down the stages of the journey at YHWH's command — a direct Torah reference to Moshe's authorship of portions of Bamidbar.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 33 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 33:2 — Moshe wrote down their starting places, stage by stage, by command of YHWH. The itinerary of Chapter 33 is explicitly described as written by Moshe at YHWH's command. This is the third explicit command to write in the Torah — after Shemot 17:14 and Devarim 31:19. The ancient record does not leave Moshe's authorship of the Torah as an implicit assumption. YHWH commands Moshe to write specific sections. Chapter 33 names forty-two stages from Egypt to the plains of Mo'av. The wilderness journey is recorded as a written document within the Torah itself.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 34  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Boundaries of the Land — The Tribal Assignees</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">YHWH spoke to Moshe, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Command the people of Yisra'EL, and say to them: When you enter the land of Kena'an — this is the land that shall fall to you for an inheritance, the land of Kena'an as defined by its borders —</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Your south side shall be from the wilderness of Tzin alongside Edom, and your southern border shall run from the end of the Dead Sea on the east.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">For the western border, you shall have the Great Sea and its coast. This shall be your western border.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:7  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">This shall be your northern border: from the Great Sea you shall draw a line to Mount Hor.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:10  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">You shall draw your eastern border from Hatzar-Enan to Shefam.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:13  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Moshe commanded the people of Yisra'EL, saying: This is the land that you shall inherit by lot, which YHWH has commanded to give to the nine tribes and to the half-tribe.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">34:17  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These are the names of the men who shall divide the land to you for inheritance: El'azar the priest and Yehoshua the son of Nun.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 34.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 34 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The boundaries of Chapter 34 define the covenant land grant with geographic precision. Southern boundary from the wilderness of Tzin to the Dead Sea. Western boundary along the Great Sea — the Mediterranean. Northern boundary from the Great Sea toward Mount Hor. Eastern boundary through the Yarden valley. The covenant land has specific defined boundaries declared by YHWH before the people have crossed the Yarden. The land is not taken through conquest and then declared covenant territory — the covenant boundary is declared before the entry and the conquest follows within those declared boundaries.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 35  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Cities of the Levites — The Cities of Refuge</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">YHWH spoke to Moshe in the plains of Mo'av by the Yarden at Yeriho, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Command the people of Yisra'EL to give to the Levites some of the inheritance of their possession as cities to dwell in. And you shall give to the Levites pasturelands around the cities.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The cities that you give to the Levites shall be the six cities of refuge, where you shall permit the manslayer to flee, and in addition to them you shall give forty-two cities.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:9  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And YHWH spoke to Moshe, saying:</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:10  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Speak to the people of Yisra'EL and say to them: When you cross the Yarden into the land of Kena'an,</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:11  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Then you shall select cities to be cities of refuge for you, that the manslayer who kills any person without intent may flee there.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:12  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The cities shall be for you a refuge from the avenger, that the manslayer may not die until he stands before the congregation for judgment.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:15  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These six cities shall be for refuge for the people of Yisra'EL, and for the stranger and for the sojourner among them, that anyone who kills any person without intent may flee there.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:30  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">If anyone kills a person, the murderer shall be put to death on the evidence of witnesses. But no person shall be put to death on the testimony of one witness.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:31  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Moreover, you shall accept no ransom for the life of a murderer who is guilty of death, but he shall be put to death.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">35:33  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">You shall not pollute the land in which you live, for blood pollutes the land, and no atonement can be made for the land for the blood that is shed in it, except by the blood of the one who shed it.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 35. The cities of refuge legislation is attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 35 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Verse 35:33 — blood pollutes the land, and no atonement can be made for the land for the blood shed in it except by the blood of the one who shed it. The land itself has a covenant sensitivity to murder. Innocent blood shed on the covenant land creates a pollution that requires specific atonement. The city of refuge system protects the unintentional manslayer from the blood avenger while preserving the principle that intentional murder requires capital accountability. The distinction between intentional killing and accidental death is one of the most developed legal frameworks in the Torah — Bamidbar 35 provides the clearest elaboration.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-bottom:1.5px solid #666666;padding-bottom:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.333em;font-weight:bold\">BAMIDBAR — CHAPTER 36  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Inheritance of the Daughters of Tzelofkhad — The Conclusion of Bamidbar</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:1  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The heads of the fathers' houses of the clan of the people of Gil'ad the son of Makhir, son of Menasheh, from the clans of the people of Yosef, came near and spoke before Moshe and before the chiefs, the heads of the fathers' houses of the people of Yisra'EL.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:2  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">They said: YHWH commanded my lord to give the land for inheritance by lot to the people of Yisra'EL, and my lord was commanded by YHWH to give the inheritance of Tzelofkhad our brother to his daughters.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:3  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">But if they are married to any of the sons of the other tribes of the people of Yisra'EL, then their inheritance will be taken from the inheritance of our fathers and added to the inheritance of the tribe into which they marry. So it will be taken away from the lot of our inheritance.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:5  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">And Moshe commanded the people of Yisra'EL according to the word of YHWH, saying: The tribe of the people of Yosef is right.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:6  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">This is what YHWH commands concerning the daughters of Tzelofkhad: Let them marry whom they think best, only they shall marry within the clan of the tribe of their father.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:10  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">The daughters of Tzelofkhad did as YHWH commanded Moshe.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:11  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">Makhlah, Tirzah, Hoglah, Milkah, and No'ah, the daughters of Tzelofkhad, married sons of their father's brothers.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.000em;font-weight:bold\">36:13  </span><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:1.000em\">These are the commandments and the rules that YHWH commanded through Moshe to the people of Yisra'EL in the plains of Mo'av by the Yarden at Yeriho.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"border-top:1px solid #aaaaaa;padding-top:0.25em\"><span style=\"color:#333333;font-size:0.905em;font-weight:bold\">COMPARATIVE MANUSCRIPT NOTES</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1a5276;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[DSS]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">4QNuma preserves portions of Chapter 36. The closing formula — verse 36:13 — is attested in the Cave 4 manuscripts.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#1e8449;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[ORIT GE'EZ]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">The Orit Ge'ez preserves Chapter 36 in full.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#7d6608;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[MASORETIC VARIANT]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">No significant variants from the DSS in this chapter.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" data-ptype=\"note\" style=\"padding-left:2.4em\"><span style=\"color:#6e2f8a;font-size:0.810em;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic\">[CRITICAL NOTE]  </span><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.810em;font-style:italic\">Bamidbar opens with a census in the wilderness of Sinai and closes in the plains of Mo'av, across the Yarden from the land of promise. The forty years are complete. The Exodus generation is gone. The new generation stands at the threshold. The last legal case of Bamidbar returns to the daughters of Tzelofkhad — whose case YHWH settled in Chapter 27 — with a refinement about tribal inheritance integrity. The book that began with the military census of the twelve tribes ends with five named women observing the covenant law precisely as YHWH commanded. They are the last individuals named in action in Bamidbar. The ancient record honors them at the closing of the fourth book.</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#222222;font-size:1.429em;font-weight:bold\">END OF BAMIDBAR — VOLUME FOUR COMPLETE</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#444444;font-size:1.048em;font-style:italic\">The Fourth Book of the Torah — Chapters 1 through 36</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#111111;font-size:3.429em;font-weight:bold;font-family:\"Segoe UI Historic\",\"Noto Sans Phoenician\",\"Noto Serif\",\"Arial Unicode MS\",serif\">𐤉𐤄𐤅𐤄</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.952em;font-style:italic\">VOLUME FOUR — TWO PARTS — NOW COMPLETE</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#666666;font-size:0.857em;font-style:italic\">Part One — Chapters 1-19 — The Census — The Camp — The Laws — The Rebellions</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#666666;font-size:0.857em;font-style:italic\">Part Two — Chapters 20-36 — The Final Years — The Oracles — The Assignments</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#555555;font-size:0.952em;font-style:italic\">CONTINUES IN VOLUME FIVE — DEVARIM</span></p>\n<p class=\"dp\" style=\"text-align:center\"><span style=\"color:#666666;font-size:0.857em;font-style:italic\">The Fifth Book of the Torah — The Words of Moshe</span></p>\n"}
